h4. Steps to reproduce
 # Create a blank page;
 # Go to [...] > Import Word Document
 # Import any word document of more than 20 MB

The import fails with the below error
{quote}The uncompressed size of your file is too large to import. You'll need to reduce the uncompressed file to 20MB or less
{quote}
The below system property doesn't make any difference to import.
{quote}CATALINA_OPTS="-Dconfluence.word.import.maxsize=30"
{quote}

h2. +*Problem*+

The [SearchManager#searchEntities API|https://docs.atlassian.com/ConfluenceServer/javadoc/7.10.1/com/atlassian/confluence/search/v2/SearchManager.html#searchEntities-com.atlassian.confluence.search.v2.ISearch-com.atlassian.confluence.search.v2.SearchManager.EntityVersionPolicy-] that we have tried to use to perform Content Searches seems to return the same list of results after reaching its limit. We passed in a [ContentSearch|https://docs.atlassian.com/ConfluenceServer/javadoc/7.10.1/com/atlassian/confluence/search/v2/ContentSearch.html] object with a {{startOffset}} and {{limit}} . We noticed we kept getting back the same results after a certain number of pages and after looking at the underlying code, there seems to be maximum {{startOffset}} of {{100,000}} and page size of {{500}}. 
 # I think documentation of this limitation in the SearchManager API docs would be helpful in the API for consumers. Both the startOffset limit of 100k and page size limit of 500 are undocumented.
 # It seems as though if we pass in an offset greater than {{100,000}}, it will just continue to use 100,000 since it does a {{Math.min(startOffset, 100000)}}. This will result in callers getting an infinite loop if they were using this as any other paged API since the returned list of items is not empty. Would it make sense to return an empty list if we have passed in an {{offset > 100,000}}

h2. +*Actual*+

{{ContentSearch search = new ContentSearch(query, sort, null, START_OFFSET, PAGE_LIMIT);}}

Both of the following search objects when passed into the #searchEntities or #search methods will return the same value.
{code:java}
ContentSearch search = new ContentSearch(query, sort, null, 100000, 500); {code}
{code:java}
ContentSearch search = new ContentSearch(query, sort, null, 100500, 500);{code}
h2.  +*Expected*+

This command should return same as before (i.e. last page of results).
{code:java}
ContentSearch search = new ContentSearch(query, sort, null, 100000, 500);{code}
This code should return an empty list (no results), to denote we have reached the limit. 
{code:java}
ContentSearch search = new ContentSearch(query, sort, null, 100500, 500);{code}
h2. +*Acceptance Criteria*+
 * Documentation is updated to denote both the Page Limit and the Start Offset Limit
 * Bug is fixed where any startOffsets > 100k will return 0 results

h1. Background:

Confluence 7.10.0 upgraded XStream to 1.4.14 and in an effort to help vendors seamlessly navigate through this significant change, {{confluence-compat-lib}} was offered with helpful methods that can fetch the correct XStream for plugins running on both pre and post XStream upgrade Confluence version with relatively low effort on the vendors' side.

This ticket is a request for an extension to that functionality as originally brought forward in CONFSERVER-60576.
h1. Summary:

I would like to suggest further extension to {{confluence-compat-lib}} to cover the non-backward compatible {{XStream#getMapper}} method. To give you a bit of context, we are using the new {{registerConverter}} method. However, our custom Converter extends from XStream's {{MapConverter}} whose constructor requires a {{com.thoughtworks.xstream.mapper.Mapper}}. This was easily obtained by running {{XStream#getClassMapper}} on XStream 1.1.1 but since this was renamed on XStream1.4.14 to {{XStream#getMapper}}, we have resorted to using reflections to cater for both cases. It would be great if the compatibility library could expose this method to enable us to register convertors more efficiently and rely completely on {{XStreamManagerCompat}} ensuring better future proofing.

{{@Component}}
 {{public class XStreamManagerCompat {}}
 {{...}}
 {{/**}}
 {{* Retrieve the Mapper.}}
 {{*}}
 {{* }}{{@return the default Mapper in XStream 1.4.x or the default ClassMapper in XStream 1.1.1.}}
 {{*/}}
 {{    public Mapper getMapper() {}}
 {{        delegate.getMapper();}}
 {{}}}
 {{}}}

 
 Thanks again for your help in making this transition as seamless as possible and for considering the suggestion brought forward here.

Ahmed.

In [Content Index Administration|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/content-index-administration-148844.html#ContentIndexAdministration-Poorperformancewhilerebuildingtheindex], it mentions the following with regards to the reindex.thread.count and index.queue.thread.count properties:
{quote}
If both reindex.thread.count and index.queue.thread.count are unset, we default to 4 threads. 
{quote}

However, [Recognized System Properties|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/recognized-system-properties-190430.html] mentions this with regards to each:

reindex.thread.count:
{quote}
* There is no default value. 
{quote}

index.queue.thread.count:
{quote}
* If you don't set index.queue.thread.count, the number of threads to be used are calculated based on the number of objects that need to be reindexed and the number of processors available (a maximum of 50 threads will be used).
* If you set index.queue.thread.count=2, then two threads will be used to reindex the content (regardless of the number of objects to be reindexed or the number of processors available)
* If you set index.queue.thread.count=200, then ten threads (the maximum allowed) will be used to reindex the content.{quote}

Could we verify which of the above statements are true and bring these two documents into agreement?

h3. Issue Summary
Code block syntax highlighting  doesn't work as expected

h3. Steps to Reproduce

 # Use sample javascript code for example:
{code}
 class User {
   constructor(name) { this.name = name; }
   sayHi() { alert(this.name); }
 }

 // class is a function
 alert(typeof User); // function

 // ...or, more precisely, the constructor method
 alert(User === User.prototype.constructor); // true

 // The methods are in User.prototype, e.g:
 alert(User.prototype.sayHi); // alert(this.name);

 // there are exactly two methods in the prototype
 alert(Object.getOwnPropertyNames(User.prototype)); // constructor, sayHi
{code}
# Create confluence page. Add new code block macro to the page, use javascript as a code highlight language
# Save the page

h3. Expected Results
Code block macro correctly highlights JS code elements (compare result from IDE, or any online code syntax parser):
 !Screenshot 2020-12-21 at 14.15.37.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Actual Results
 !Screenshot 2020-12-21 at 14.58.09.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Workaround
 Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
Styling of the text with dash and tab in front will be broken when previewing in Office Word Macro.
The issue is currently not observable in Confluence 7.4.x

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a word document, that has a dash (minus), then tab, then some larger text.  [^Word macro - alignment issue.docx] 
 # Import this document into Confluence.
 # Create Office Word macro from the document.

h3. Expected Results
Styling will be exactly like in a Word document.
 !Screen Shot 2020-12-16 at 12.27.39.png|thumbnail! 


h3. Actual Results
Styling is broken completely.
 !Screen Shot 2020-12-16 at 12.27.25.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Workaround
Applying this javascript in Confluence Administration > Custom HTML will fix the issue:
{code}
<script>
AJS.toInit(function() {
setTimeout(function() {
var paragraph=$( ".office-document div p" );
paragraph.children().css( "width", "auto" );
        }, 500);
 });
</script>
{code}
